<section>
<h1 id="why-the-codex-isnt-a-wiki">Why the Codex Isn't a Wiki</h1>
<p><em>A 657-PDF personal library, three public positions from April 2026, and what the model-owned thinking surface actually costs.</em></p>
<br/>
<p>April 2026 has seen a 'moment' for personal knowledge management over LLMs. <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Andrej Karpathy</a> published a lengthy tweet. <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Artem Zhutov</a> ran an empirical rebuttal two weeks later. <a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Simon Willison</a>, quieter as usual, had already written the architecture that both were arguing around. Watching them triangulate in real time felt like synchronicity — it landed just as I was thinking about what my own corpus should become.</p>
<p>I'll tell you where I landed, and why, but the shortest version is this: my codex of 657 PDFs is not becoming a wiki. It's becoming something stricter and, I think, more durable.</p>
<h2 id="the-scale-problem-nobody-names">The scale problem nobody names</h2>
<p>Personal corpora sit in a strange middle. They're too big to paste into context — 657 documents is not a lunchtime read. But they're too small for research-grade infrastructure — Neo4j and GraphRAG are machinery for tens of thousands of documents and teams of people. The patterns that work for a startup's knowledge base collapse under the weight of their own ceremony when one person uses them. The patterns that work for a single web search don't scale to a lifetime of reading.</p>
<p>This is the scale where <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>, <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>, and <a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a> are all writing. It's also the scale where most of us actually live — a Kindle, a Drive folder, a filesystem of saved PDFs we haven't re-read.</p>
<p>The question is not <em>whether</em> the model helps you think over your corpus. Everyone agrees it does. The question is <em>how much machinery you build between the raw documents and the query</em>, and <em>who owns what the machinery produces</em>.</p>
<h2 id="karpathys-proposal-compile-it"><a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>'s proposal: compile it</h2>
<p>The tweet <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a> published in early April describes a pattern he calls the LLM Wiki. Raw documents go into a <code>raw/</code> directory. An LLM agent reads each source and writes a summary. It extracts people, places, concepts, and technical terms into their own pages. It builds backlinks and cross-references. It compiles a schema file that tells future queries where to look. You view the wiki in Obsidian. <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a> is explicit that he rarely touches it directly. The model is the maintainer.</p>
<p>The seduction here is real. If it works, you get a continuously growing, structurally navigable map of everything you've read, organised by concept rather than filename, with the latent connections — the ones you'd never find by searching for keywords you can't remember — surfaced automatically. It's close to what a good human librarian produces for you, at machine speed.</p>
<p>It also has an implicit bet at its core: that the compile step is cheap enough to run continuously, and that a model at query time will <em>use</em> the compiled artifact rather than going back to the raw sources. Both halves of that bet are load-bearing. If either fails, you've paid for a lot of prose that nothing reads.</p>
<h2 id="zhutovs-test-the-bet-failed"><a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s test: the bet failed</h2>
<p>On 19 April, <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Artem Zhutov</a> published an X thread that I'd call the most important empirical contribution to this conversation so far. He took <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>'s pattern seriously enough to actually build it. Nineteen sources on Ray Dalio's decision-making framework. Twenty minutes to ingest. He asked the wiki ten questions, and he asked the same ten questions of NotebookLM — Google's embedding-over-raw-sources tool — on the same documents.</p>
<p>The results were uncomfortable for the wiki.</p>
<p>At query time, Claude <em>ignored the compiled artifact</em>. It bypassed the entity pages, bypassed the summaries, and re-read the full source transcripts to answer. Forty-four thousand tokens per question. The compile work had happened; the retrieval didn't consume it.</p>
<p>NotebookLM, which had done no compile work at all — only embeddings — answered the same ten questions at a fraction of the cost, in about a minute each, with citations back to the source transcripts. Same quality. Sometimes better.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s second critique cut deeper than the cost one. Even when the wiki <em>does</em> work, he asked, <em>so what?</em> You have a beautifully structured knowledge base. It sits there. It does not integrate with your morning routine or your decision-making or your writing. It is static storage dressed up as thinking. His move was to abandon the wiki frame entirely and reshape his Dalio reading into a skill — a callable decision-making template, invoked from a daily routine, consulted at the moment a decision is in front of him. The storage was not the valuable artifact. The reusable action was.</p>
<p>And then a note that deserves its own paragraph: the token era has shifted. <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a> writes from inside the change. January was unlimited; April is tight. Patterns that assumed subsidised tokens are breaking now, in public. Anyone designing for the next five years of a corpus has to design assuming tokens cost what they cost.</p>
<h2 id="willisons-architecture-already-solved-quietly"><a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a>'s architecture: already solved, quietly</h2>
<p><a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Simon Willison</a> has been writing about this stack for longer than either of them, in smaller increments, without the headline-grabbing post. His position is architecturally conservative and, I think, correct.</p>
<p>Three things he's put his weight behind:</p>
<p>Hybrid retrieval over raw sources — specifically, FTS5 for keyword search (which matters for names and acronyms embeddings miss), sqlite-vec for vector search (which matters for concept match), and Reciprocal Rank Fusion to combine them without the embarrassment of comparing incommensurable scores. Alex Garcia, <a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a>'s collaborator, has published the canonical worked implementation. This is the stack NotebookLM is doing a variant of; it's the stack I'm building; and it's the stack <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s test vindicates.</p>
<p>Cooling on classic RAG. <a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a>'s exact phrase: <em>"I've recently found myself cooling a little on the classic RAG pattern of finding relevant documents and dumping them into the context for a single call to an LLM."</em> He favours iterative tool-use — multiple retrieval calls across a single answer, the agent reading the first hits, narrowing by tag, pulling a specific passage on demand. Retrieval as a live dialogue, not a one-shot dump.</p>
<p>Search primitives should be good enough for a human to use directly. Quoting Panda Smith: <em>"If you want to make a good RAG tool that uses your documentation, you should start by making a search engine over those documents that would be good enough for a human to use themselves."</em> Search is first-class. It's not a hidden step inside an agent loop. The human queries too.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a> doesn't argue with <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a> directly. He doesn't have to. The stack he's been quietly documenting for years is the one <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s test proves viable, and the absence of any compile step in it is the point.</p>
<h2 id="the-axis-they-split-on">The axis they split on</h2>
<p>Strip the examples and the three positions line up on one axis: how much pre-compilation sits between raw documents and the query.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>: heavy. Continuous prose wiki, per concept, continuously maintained, model-owned.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a>: light. A hybrid index at ingest — embeddings and FTS, nothing else — and iterative tool-use at query time.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>: minimal. Embeddings at ingest, and then the distillation happens <em>above</em> retrieval, as skills and templates invoked in context.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a> and <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a> agree on the ingest side. They differ on what sits above it — <a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a> wants composable CLI tools, <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a> wants action-embedded skills. Both of them disagree with <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a> about the middle layer: neither wants a prose wiki maintained by the model as the default navigable surface.</p>
<p>The empirical weight of <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s test pushes me toward their side of the axis.</p>
<h2 id="what-the-codex-takes-from-each">What the codex takes from each</h2>
<p>In dialogue with Sonnet 4.6, it became apparent I would like to share this collaborative thinking space with my son in twenty or thirty years, and I want it to cost me a sensible amount each month. Those two constraints — inheritance and affordability — are not <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>'s concerns. They are mine.</p>
<p>The design, in a sentence: hybrid retrieval over raw sources (<a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a>), committed distillation into reusable actions (<a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s instinct, my shape), no continuous prose wiki (<a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>'s pattern, rejected with evidence).</p>
<p>Concretely, three primitives do the work:</p>
<ul>
<li><code>codex.search</code> is the hybrid FTS5 + sqlite-vec + RRF query, exposed as a CLI, a Telegram command, and a skill. It's good enough for me to use by hand, which is <a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a>'s test.</li>
<li><code>codex.read</code> pulls a known document into context by path or pattern. It's the move I already make by reflex — <em>read /codex/trading/*no sense*</em> — and it deserves to be a first-class primitive, not a degenerate case of search.</li>
<li><code>codex.apply</code> composes a lens (a framework extracted from one set of corpus documents) onto a source (another document, an article, a draft). Its output is a CaseBook draft with per-claim provenance: which claim came from the corpus, which from trained knowledge, which from this session. I commit the CaseBook or discard it. The model proposes; I dispose.</li>
</ul>
<p>The CaseBook is where my distilled thinking lives. It is not a wiki page. It is a committed, reusable, invocable view — closer in shape to <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s skills than to <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>'s concept pages. It carries its provenance with it. It can be applied again, edited, or retired.</p>
<h2 id="the-principle-that-governs-the-whole-thing">The principle that governs the whole thing</h2>
<p>Let's keep this as simple as possible:</p>
<p>Compiled artifacts earn their compile cost only when they are consumed at retrieval time.</p>
<p>Phase 2 enrichment — concept fingerprints, entities, related-docs — passes this test because <code>codex.search</code> consumes it on every query. It is retrieval fuel. It earns its place every time the search runs.</p>
<p>A continuously maintained prose wiki fails this test. <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s measurement is the evidence: the model does not read the wiki at query time. It goes to the raw sources. The compile cost is paid; the retrieval benefit is not received. The wiki is dead cargo.</p>
<p>A browseable concept index as a separate navigation layer — which I considered, and which was my weaker intermediate position — also fails, for the same reason. Once <code>codex.search</code> already consumes the enrichment deterministically, a second navigable surface is redundant. I'd be paying to render what the retrieval already uses.</p>
<p>The principle rules out more than it rules in. That's what I want from it.</p>
<h2 id="the-twenty-year-frame">The twenty-year frame</h2>
<p>There's a last layer to this that the public conversation mostly misses. I'm not optimising only for next week's query. I'm optimising for what my son inherits, and for what his AI — whatever that is in 2046 — can still read.</p>
<p>This is why the canonical format stays PDF. Text is a cache, derived and regenerable. It's why the metadata lives in SQLite with an export command that produces a self-contained tarball. It's why taxonomy decisions are recorded as markdown files, not absorbed into config. It's why CaseBooks are markdown with explicit provenance manifests — because the thing I most want to pass on is not the corpus itself but the thinking I did on top of it, in a form that's still readable after the LLMs we use now are gone.</p>
<p><a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a>'s wiki doesn't fail on inheritance — prose is portable. But it fails on affordability and on consumption ratio, and my son doesn't inherit what I can't afford to maintain.</p>
<h2 id="whats-worth-keeping-from-karpathy">What's worth keeping from <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a></h2>
<p>He's right that raw-documents-plus-retrieval leaves value on the table. That instinct is correct. What he gets wrong is the shape the distillation should take. A continuously maintained prose wiki, owned by the model, is the wrong answer for personal scale in the current token economy. A committed, person-authored, reusable CaseBook that composes with <code>codex.apply</code> is, I think, the right one.</p>
<p>The rejection is the useful part to record. Not the wiki as an enemy — <a href="https://x.com/karpathy" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Karpathy</a> is onto something (when isn't he?), the pattern is interesting, and in a team context with research-grade budgets it may well be right. But in my context, at my scale, with my constraints, it is the wrong bet. <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a>'s test is the evidence I needed to see before I built the wrong thing myself.</p>
<p>The codex (what I call my system) keeps its raw sources. It builds a retrieval stack <a href="https://x.com/simonw" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Willison</a> would recognise. It distils into CaseBooks <a href="https://x.com/artemzh" rel="noopener" style="text-decoration: underline; color: blue;" target="_blank">Zhutov</a> would call skills. And it writes down why, so whoever reads this next — including my son — knows not just what was decided, but which April 2026 thinking it stood on.</p>
<p><em>Draft, 2026-04-20.</em></p>
</section>
